tent of the book is predominantly prototype, as it examines subjects that have not previously been discussed in the past. These include: a) The generic interaction between the ‘host’ genre of love elegy, and several ‘guest’ genres (e.g., Roman comedy, epic, pastoral); b) The hidden metapoetic discourse regarding the genre of love elegy itself. The book is intended for scholars or students working on or interested in Roman love elegy and its generic evolution in Late Antiquity.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 4aLiebeslyrik. 4aMaximianus, Etruscus. 4aMetapoetik. 4aSpätantike. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aMaximianus Etruscus, latin love poetry, late antiquity, metapoetics.0 cEPUBz97831107706120 cprintz978311077037740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110770476423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110770476/original  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK